<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rubriflora">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea rubriflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most easily distinguished from similar species by the erect, rostrate fruiting capsule combined with the lobed leaves and slightly longer sepals. However, some specimens such as 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Hieronymus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hieronymus</taxonomicName>
s.n.
</emphasis>
[10/1879] (BM); 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">D.O. King</emphasis>
731 (BM) have erect muticous capsules although the sepals are too large for 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hederifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea hederifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
so presumably belong to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rubriflora">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea rubriflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
